    content: `**8.1. Personal Protective Equipment (PPE):**
● All Three Mile Fire Department ambulances (3040/3045) must carry the following minimum PPE for each crew member:
○ Disposable non-latex gloves (various sizes)
○ Eye protection (goggles or safety glasses)
○ Surgical masks
○ N95 or equivalent respirators
○ Fluid-impervious disposable gowns
○ Puncture-resistant sharps containers
○ High-visibility safety vests (for traffic control/roadside incidents)
● N95/Airborne Pathogen Protocol: Personnel must don an N95 respirator mask before entering the scene and maintain it throughout the call if:
○ The patient is exhibiting signs/symptoms of an airborne infectious disease (e.g., active, persistent cough with fever, Tuberculosis exposure, etc.).
○ Aerosol Generating Procedures (AGPs) are anticipated or performed (e.g., intubation, deep suctioning, Continuous Positive Airway Pressure (CPAP), nebulized medication administration).

**8.2. Traffic Control (Scene Blocking):**
● At roadside incidents, the first arriving unit (either 3040 or 3045) shall establish a safe working area by positioning the vehicle to block the immediate incident area from oncoming traffic.
● Personal working on any kind of roadway, street, public traffic, parking log, or around vehicles with wear a high visibility vest. There should be enough vest for all crew of the ambulance. If vest are missing, defective, or incorrect number, Three Mile Fire Department EMS Officer should be notified as soon as possible.

**Traffic Control Steps for MVA:**
1. Scene Size-up (Safety First): Assess scene hazards (traffic speed, vehicle damage, wires, fluids).
2. Initial Blocking: Position the first apparatus (Engine or Ambulance) uphill and upwind if possible, creating a barrier with the vehicle's body to shield the work area. Angle the front wheels away from the work zone.
3. Apparatus Lights: Engage all warning lights, including strobes and turn signals pointing toward the direction traffic should merge.
4. Cones/Flares: Deploy cones, flares, or temporary traffic control devices upstream to give oncoming traffic advance warning, beginning approximately 150 feet from the scene.
5. Designate Safety Officer: Assign a dedicated safety officer or personnel to maintain awareness of traffic flow and scene perimeter.

**8.3. Incident Decontamination:**
● Gross decontamination of reusable equipment (e.g., stretchers, backboards) must occur at the scene prior to leaving, if possible.
● Ambulances must be thoroughly cleaned and disinfected upon return to the station after every patient contact involving exposure to body fluids.
● Any Three Mile Fire Department equipment that went with patient to the hospital or receiving facilities that is not disposable and not collected on EMS crew departure from the facility should be reported to Three Mile Fire Department EMS Officer as soon as possible so the equipment can be retrieved or replaced.`,
