    title: '11.0 Communications (Montana Specific)',
    content: `**11.1. Montana Statewide Interoperability (SWIC) Radio Channels:**
While specific channel names vary by region, the following colors represent standard, critical EMS communications channels in Montana's statewide interoperable system:
**Channel Color | Purpose/Usage:**
**RED** | State Fire Mutual Aid: Should be the first choice for on scene interagency communications
**SCARLET** | State Fire Ground #2
**CORAL** | State Fire Ground #1
**WHITE** | Hospital-to-Ambulance and Hospital-to-Hospital Communications
**TAN** | Primary Use: State Air-to-Ground Coordination. Secondary Use: EMS communications and medical staging at an incident scene
**GOLD** | Statewide/Mutual Aid: Used for communications with distant jurisdictions or during massive statewide events.
**SILVER** | Law Enforcement Mutual Aid
**RUBY** | State Fire Repeater
**GARNET** | State Fire Repeater Control
**MAROON** | State Command & Control
**COPPER** | State Fire Ground #3
**BURGUNDY** | State Fire Ground #4
**GRAY** | Primary Use: Central Region Dispatch & Paging. Secondary Use: On-scene incident management per SOP (Treatment Group)
**PINK** | Primary Use: Western/Eastern Region Dispatch & Paging. Secondary Use: On-scene incident management per SOP (Transport Group)
**NEON** | General Mutual Aid and Coordination Note: EMS Priority during mass casualty incidents. On-scene incident management per SOP (Triage Group)
**VIOLET** | National Search and Rescue
**PURPLE** | State Search and Rescue
**SCHOOL** | School Emergency Used only during school emergencies to provide a direct communications link between the school and law enforcement
**BROWN** | State DES Direction and Control Use only per SOP or State DES approval
**GREEN** | State/Federal Common This cooperative frequency may be used only for forest firefighting and conservation activities. It also must be coordinated with the U.S. Dept. of Agriculture.

**11.2. Hospital Short Report Protocol (MIST Format):**
The minimum required patient report to be given to the receiving hospital (Trauma, STEMI, Stroke) via radio or phone (when available) upon leaving the scene or shortly before arrival:
**Acronym | Detail:**
**M** | Mechanism of Injury (e.g., Rollover MVA at 60 MPH) OR Medical Complaint (e.g., Chest Pain)
**I** | Injuries (e.g., Open fracture of the femur) OR Illness (e.g., History of CHF)
**S** | Signs/Symptoms and Vitals (e.g., BP 90/60, HR 120, GCS 15)
**T** | Treatment given (e.g., IV initiated, 2mg Morphine administered, Tourniquet applied)`,
